   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Lecture 10 — Dimensionality Reduction & PCA\n",
    "\n",
    "**Practice covered:** L10 – PCA\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## The Curse of Dimensionality\n",
    "\n",
    "MNIST digits have 784 features. Housing data might have 100 features after feature engineering. Many ML algorithms slow down dramatically with high dimensions, and visualization is impossible beyond 3D.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Dimensionality reduction:** map data from $D$ dimensions to $M$ dimensions where $M \\ll D$, while **preserving as much information as possible**.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Applications:**\n",
    "- Visualization (reduce to 2D or 3D to plot)\n",
    "- Speed up subsequent ML algorithms\n",
    "- Remove noise (small variance = mostly noise)\n",
    "- Feature compression (e.g., image compression)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "%matplotlib inline\n",
    "\n",
    "# Motivating example: 2D data with a clear \"main direction\"\n",
    "np.random.seed(42)\n",
    "t = np.random.randn(100)\n",
    "X_2d = np.column_stack([\n",
    "    2*t + 0.2*np.random.randn(100),   # x1 ≈ 2*t\n",
    "    1*t + 0.2*np.random.randn(100)    # x2 ≈ 1*t\n",
    "])\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(6, 5))\n",
    "plt.scatter(X_2d[:,0], X_2d[:,1], alpha=0.6)\n",
    "plt.xlabel('x₁'); plt.ylabel('x₂')\n",
    "plt.title('2D data with correlated features\\n(most variance along one direction)')\n",
    "plt.axis('equal'); plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3); plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Correlation between x₁ and x₂: {np.corrcoef(X_2d[:,0], X_2d[:,1])[0,1]:.3f}\")\n",
    "print(\"Highly correlated → we can probably represent this in 1D without losing much info\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Part 1 — What Direction Has the Most Variance?\n",
    "\n",
    "Imagine projecting all data points onto a line through the origin. Different line directions capture different amounts of the data's spread.\n",
    "\n",
    "**PCA finds the direction(s) that maximize variance** — the directions where the data is most spread out.\n",
    "\n",
    "Why maximize variance?\n",
    "- High variance = the data varies a lot along that direction = that direction carries information\n",
    "- Low variance = data is nearly constant along that direction = that direction is mostly noise"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Visualize: projecting onto different directions captures different amounts of variance\n",
    "X_c = X_2d - X_2d.mean(axis=0)  # center data first\n",
    "\n",
    "angles = np.linspace(0, np.pi, 7)\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 4, figsize=(15, 7))\n",
    "\n",
    "variances = []\n",
    "for ax, angle in zip(axes.flat, angles):\n",
    "    direction = np.array([np.cos(angle), np.sin(angle)])\n",
    "    projections = X_c @ direction        # scalar projection of each point\n",
    "    variance = np.var(projections)\n",
    "    variances.append(variance)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    ax.scatter(X_c[:,0], X_c[:,1], alpha=0.4, s=20)\n",
    "    # Draw the projection line\n",
    "    scale = 3\n",
    "    ax.plot([-scale*direction[0], scale*direction[0]], \n",
    "            [-scale*direction[1], scale*direction[1]], 'r-', linewidth=2)\n",
    "    # Show projected points on the line\n",
    "    proj_pts = np.outer(projections, direction)\n",
    "    ax.scatter(proj_pts[:,0], proj_pts[:,1], c='red', s=10, alpha=0.6)\n",
    "    ax.set_title(f'angle={np.degrees(angle):.0f}°\\nvar={variance:.2f}')\n",
    "    ax.set_xlim(-6, 6); ax.set_ylim(-4, 4); ax.axis('equal'); ax.grid(True, alpha=0.2)\n",
    "\n",
    "axes.flat[-1].axis('off')  # hide last subplot\n",
    "plt.suptitle('Variance captured by projecting onto different directions', y=1.02)\n",
    "plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "best_angle = angles[np.argmax(variances)]\n",
    "print(f\"Best angle: {np.degrees(best_angle):.1f}° → max variance: {max(variances):.2f}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Part 2 — The Covariance Matrix: A Map of Relationships\n",
    "\n",
    "The **covariance matrix** $\\Sigma$ encodes how features vary *together*:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\Sigma = \\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{n=1}^N (\\mathbf{x}_n - \\bar{\\mathbf{x}})(\\mathbf{x}_n - \\bar{\\mathbf{x}})^T = \\frac{1}{N} X^T X$$\n",
    "\n",
    "(after centering $X$)\n",
    "\n",
    "- $\\Sigma_{ii}$ = variance of feature $i$\n",
    "- $\\Sigma_{ij}$ = covariance of features $i$ and $j$ (how much they vary together)\n",
    "\n",
    "**The direction of maximum variance is the eigenvector of $\\Sigma$ with the largest eigenvalue.** This is a fundamental result from linear algebra."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Compute covariance matrix\n",
    "N = X_c.shape[0]\n",
    "Sigma = (1/N) * X_c.T @ X_c   # shape (2, 2)\n",
    "print(\"Covariance matrix:\")\n",
    "print(Sigma.round(3))\n",
    "print(f\"\\nVar(x₁) = {Sigma[0,0]:.3f}, Var(x₂) = {Sigma[1,1]:.3f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Cov(x₁,x₂) = {Sigma[0,1]:.3f}  (positive = they move together)\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Part 3 — Eigendecomposition: Finding the Principal Directions\n",
    "\n",
    "An **eigenvector** of $\\Sigma$ is a direction that, when transformed by $\\Sigma$, only gets scaled (not rotated):\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\Sigma \\mathbf{u} = \\lambda \\mathbf{u}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "- $\\mathbf{u}$ = eigenvector = the principal direction\n",
    "- $\\lambda$ = eigenvalue = how much variance is in that direction\n",
    "\n",
    "For a $D \\times D$ covariance matrix, there are $D$ eigenvector-eigenvalue pairs. Sort them by eigenvalue descending — the first is the direction of maximum variance (PC1), the second is orthogonal to it with second-most variance (PC2), etc."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Eigendecomposition\n",
    "eigenvalues, eigenvectors = np.linalg.eig(Sigma)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Sort by eigenvalue descending\n",
    "order = np.argsort(eigenvalues)[::-1]\n",
    "eigenvalues = eigenvalues[order].real\n",
    "eigenvectors = eigenvectors[:, order].real\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Eigenvalues (= variance in each principal direction):\")\n",
    "print(f\"  PC1: λ₁ = {eigenvalues[0]:.4f}  (u₁ = {eigenvectors[:,0].round(3)})\")\n",
    "print(f\"  PC2: λ₂ = {eigenvalues[1]:.4f}  (u₂ = {eigenvectors[:,1].round(3)})\")\n",
    "print(f\"\\nPC1 explains {eigenvalues[0]/eigenvalues.sum()*100:.1f}% of variance\")\n",
    "print(f\"PC2 explains {eigenvalues[1]/eigenvalues.sum()*100:.1f}% of variance\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Visualize principal components\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(6, 5))\n",
    "plt.scatter(X_c[:,0], X_c[:,1], alpha=0.5, label='Data (centered)')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Draw principal components scaled by sqrt(eigenvalue)\n",
    "for i, (lam, u, color, label) in enumerate(zip(\n",
    "    eigenvalues, eigenvectors.T,\n",
    "    ['red', 'blue'],\n",
    "    ['PC1 (most variance)', 'PC2 (least variance)'])):\n",
    "    scale = np.sqrt(lam) * 2\n",
    "    plt.arrow(0, 0, scale*u[0], scale*u[1], \n",
    "              head_width=0.1, head_length=0.05, fc=color, ec=color, linewidth=2, label=label)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.axis('equal'); plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "plt.xlabel('x₁'); plt.ylabel('x₂')\n",
    "plt.title('Principal components = eigenvectors of covariance matrix\\n(arrow length ∝ variance explained)')\n",
    "plt.legend(); plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Part 4 — Projecting: Dimensionality Reduction in Action\n",
    "\n",
    "To reduce from $D$ to $M$ dimensions:\n",
    "1. Take the top $M$ eigenvectors as columns of matrix $U$ (shape $D \\times M$)\n",
    "2. Project: $\\mathbf{z} = U^T (\\mathbf{x} - \\bar{\\mathbf{x}})$\n",
    "\n",
    "This is the *projection onto the principal subspace* — the subspace that preserves maximum variance.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Reconstruction** (approximate): $\\hat{\\mathbf{x}} = U \\mathbf{z} + \\bar{\\mathbf{x}}$\n",
    "\n",
    "The reconstruction error is the information lost, controlled by how many PCs you keep."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Project 2D data onto 1D (PC1 only)\n",
    "U1 = eigenvectors[:, :1]   # shape (2, 1) — just PC1\n",
    "Z = X_c @ U1               # shape (100, 1) — 1D representation\n",
    "X_recon = Z @ U1.T         # shape (100, 2) — approximate reconstruction\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(7, 5))\n",
    "plt.scatter(X_c[:,0], X_c[:,1], alpha=0.5, label='Original 2D', s=30)\n",
    "plt.scatter(X_recon[:,0], X_recon[:,1], alpha=0.5, c='red', label='Reconstructed (from 1D)', s=30)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Draw reconstruction error lines\n",
    "for i in range(0, 100, 5):\n",
    "    plt.plot([X_c[i,0], X_recon[i,0]], [X_c[i,1], X_recon[i,1]], 'gray', alpha=0.3, linewidth=0.8)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Draw PC1 axis\n",
    "u1 = eigenvectors[:,0]\n",
    "scale = 5\n",
    "plt.plot([-scale*u1[0], scale*u1[0]], [-scale*u1[1], scale*u1[1]], 'b-', linewidth=2, label='PC1 axis')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.axis('equal'); plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "plt.xlabel('x₁'); plt.ylabel('x₂')\n",
    "plt.title('1D projection: data projected onto PC1\\n(gray lines = reconstruction error)')\n",
    "plt.legend(); plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "total_variance = np.var(X_c, axis=0).sum()\n",
    "recon_error = np.mean(np.sum((X_c - X_recon)**2, axis=1))\n",
    "print(f\"Reconstruction error: {recon_error:.4f}  ({recon_error/total_variance*100:.1f}% of total variance lost)\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Part 5 — Full PCA Pipeline (as in Practice L10)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def pca(X, num_components):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Full PCA pipeline — exactly the structure expected in Practice L10.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Steps:\n",
    "    1. Normalize (zero mean, unit std)\n",
    "    2. Compute covariance matrix\n",
    "    3. Eigendecomposition\n",
    "    4. Sort components by eigenvalue (largest first)\n",
    "    5. Select top k components\n",
    "    6. Project data\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    m, n = X.shape\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Step 1: Normalize\n",
    "    mu = X.mean(axis=0)            # feature means\n",
    "    sigma = X.std(axis=0)           # feature std deviations\n",
    "    X_norm = (X - mu) / sigma       # z-score normalization\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Step 2: Covariance matrix (n×n)\n",
    "    Sigma = (1/m) * X_norm.T @ X_norm\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Step 3: Eigendecomposition\n",
    "    eigenvalues, eigenvectors = np.linalg.eig(Sigma)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Step 4: Sort by eigenvalue descending\n",
    "    order = np.argsort(eigenvalues)[::-1]\n",
    "    eigenvalues = eigenvalues[order].real\n",
    "    eigenvectors = eigenvectors[:, order].real   # columns = principal components\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Step 5: Select top k components\n",
    "    U = eigenvectors[:, :num_components]          # shape (n, k)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Step 6: Project\n",
    "    X_reduced = X_norm @ U                        # shape (m, k)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Explained variance ratio\n",
    "    explained_var = eigenvalues[:num_components].sum() / eigenvalues.sum()\n",
    "    \n",
    "    return X_reduced, U, eigenvalues, explained_var, mu, sigma\n",
    "\n",
    "# Apply to sklearn digits dataset\n",
    "from sklearn.datasets import load_digits\n",
    "digits = load_digits()\n",
    "X_dig = digits.data.astype(float)\n",
    "Y_dig = digits.target\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Original: {X_dig.shape}  ({X_dig.shape[1]} features per image)\")\n",
    "\n",
    "for k in [2, 10, 30]:\n",
    "    X_red, U, eigvals, var, mu, sigma = pca(X_dig, k)\n",
    "    print(f\"  k={k:2d}: {X_red.shape}  explains {var:.1%} of variance\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Scree plot: how many components do you need?\n",
    "_, _, eigvals_all, _, _, _ = pca(X_dig, X_dig.shape[1])\n",
    "\n",
    "cum_var = np.cumsum(eigvals_all) / eigvals_all.sum()\n",
    "k_90 = np.searchsorted(cum_var, 0.90) + 1\n",
    "k_95 = np.searchsorted(cum_var, 0.95) + 1\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 4))\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[0].plot(eigvals_all[:30], 'bo-', markersize=5)\n",
    "axes[0].set_xlabel('Component'); axes[0].set_ylabel('Eigenvalue')\n",
    "axes[0].set_title('Scree plot: eigenvalue per component\\n(\"elbow\" = good cutoff)')\n",
    "axes[0].grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[1].plot(np.arange(1, len(cum_var)+1), cum_var * 100, 'r-', linewidth=2)\n",
    "axes[1].axhline(90, color='blue', linestyle='--', label=f'90% variance → k={k_90}')\n",
    "axes[1].axhline(95, color='green', linestyle='--', label=f'95% variance → k={k_95}')\n",
    "axes[1].set_xlabel('Number of components k'); axes[1].set_ylabel('Cumulative variance (%)')\n",
    "axes[1].set_title('How many components to keep?')\n",
    "axes[1].legend(); axes[1].grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()\n",
    "print(f\"Need {k_90} components for 90% variance (vs 64 original features — {k_90/64*100:.0f}% of original)\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Visualize: 2D projection of 64D digit data\n",
    "X_2d_dig, _, _, _, _, _ = pca(X_dig, 2)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))\n",
    "colors = plt.cm.tab10(np.linspace(0, 1, 10))\n",
    "for digit in range(10):\n",
    "    mask = Y_dig == digit\n",
    "    plt.scatter(X_2d_dig[mask, 0], X_2d_dig[mask, 1],\n",
    "                c=[colors[digit]], label=str(digit), alpha=0.6, s=20)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.xlabel('PC1'); plt.ylabel('PC2')\n",
    "plt.title('MNIST digits projected to 2D via PCA\\n(64 features → 2 features for visualization)')\n",
    "plt.legend(title='Digit', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1)); plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Image compression: reconstruct from k components\n",
    "sample_idx = 42\n",
    "sample = X_dig[sample_idx:sample_idx+1]\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 5, figsize=(12, 3))\n",
    "axes[0].imshow(sample.reshape(8,8), cmap='gray'); axes[0].set_title('Original'); axes[0].axis('off')\n",
    "\n",
    "for ax, k in zip(axes[1:], [1, 5, 15, 30]):\n",
    "    _, U_k, _, var_k, mu_k, sigma_k = pca(X_dig, k)\n",
    "    # Project and reconstruct\n",
    "    sample_norm = (sample - mu_k) / sigma_k\n",
    "    z = sample_norm @ U_k             # (1, k) — compressed\n",
    "    recon_norm = z @ U_k.T            # (1, 64) — reconstructed\n",
    "    recon = recon_norm * sigma_k + mu_k\n",
    "    ax.imshow(recon.reshape(8,8), cmap='gray')\n",
    "    ax.set_title(f'k={k}\\n{var_k:.0%} var')\n",
    "    ax.axis('off')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.suptitle('Image reconstruction with increasing number of PCA components')\n",
    "plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Part 6 — The High-Dimensional Trick\n",
    "\n",
    "For MNIST with 784 features and 5000 samples, computing the $784 \\times 784$ covariance matrix is expensive, and it has 5000 nonzero eigenvalues at most.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Efficient trick for $D \\gg N$:** Compute eigenvectors of the $N \\times N$ matrix $\\frac{1}{N} X X^T$ instead. Then recover the full eigenvectors:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\mathbf{u}^{(i)} = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{N \\lambda_i}} X^T \\mathbf{v}^{(i)}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Same result, much cheaper when $N \\ll D$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Demonstrate: both approaches give same projections\n",
    "np.random.seed(0)\n",
    "m_small, d = 50, 200   # 50 samples, 200 features (D >> N)\n",
    "X_hd = np.random.randn(m_small, d)\n",
    "X_hd_c = X_hd - X_hd.mean(axis=0)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Standard: D×D covariance\n",
    "Sigma_DD = (1/m_small) * X_hd_c.T @ X_hd_c       # (200, 200)\n",
    "evals_DD, evecs_DD = np.linalg.eig(Sigma_DD)\n",
    "order = np.argsort(evals_DD.real)[::-1]\n",
    "U_standard = evecs_DD[:, order[:3]].real           # top 3 components\n",
    "\n",
    "# Efficient: N×N matrix\n",
    "G = (1/m_small) * X_hd_c @ X_hd_c.T              # (50, 50) — much smaller!\n",
    "evals_NN, evecs_NN = np.linalg.eig(G)\n",
    "order2 = np.argsort(evals_NN.real)[::-1]\n",
    "evecs_NN = evecs_NN[:, order2[:3]].real\n",
    "evals_NN = evals_NN[order2[:3]].real\n",
    "# Recover D-dimensional eigenvectors\n",
    "U_efficient = np.column_stack([\n",
    "    X_hd_c.T @ evecs_NN[:, i] / np.sqrt(m_small * evals_NN[i])\n",
    "    for i in range(3)\n",
    "])\n",
    "\n",
    "# Compare projections\n",
    "Z_std = X_hd_c @ U_standard\n",
    "Z_eff = X_hd_c @ U_efficient\n",
    "\n",
    "# They may differ in sign (eigenvectors are defined up to sign flip)\n",
    "for i in range(3):\n",
    "    if np.corrcoef(Z_std[:,i], Z_eff[:,i])[0,1] < 0:\n",
    "        Z_eff[:,i] *= -1\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Correlation between standard and efficient PCA projections:\")\n",
    "for i in range(3):\n",
    "    corr = np.corrcoef(Z_std[:,i], Z_eff[:,i])[0,1]\n",
    "    print(f\"  PC{i+1}: {corr:.6f}  (should be ~1.0)\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Summary\n",
    "\n",
    "**PCA Algorithm (for Practice L10):**\n",
    "```python\n",
    "# Step 1: Normalize\n",
    "mu = X.mean(axis=0)\n",
    "sigma = X.std(axis=0)\n",
    "X_norm = (X - mu) / sigma\n",
    "\n",
    "# Step 2: Covariance matrix\n",
    "Sigma = (1/m) * X_norm.T @ X_norm    # (n, n)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Step 3: Eigen-decomposition\n",
    "eigenvalues, eigenvectors = np.linalg.eig(Sigma)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Step 4: Sort descending\n",
    "order = np.argsort(eigenvalues)[::-1]\n",
    "eigenvectors = eigenvectors[:, order].real  # columns sorted\n",
    "\n",
    "# Step 5: Project\n",
    "U = eigenvectors[:, :k]          # top k components: (n, k)\n",
    "X_reduced = X_norm @ U           # (m, k)\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "**What eigenvalues tell you:**\n",
    "- Large eigenvalue → that direction has high variance → important to keep\n",
    "- Small eigenvalue → that direction has low variance → can discard\n",
    "\n",
    "**How many components to keep:**\n",
    "- Retain components until cumulative variance ≥ 90–95%\n",
    "- OR look for the \"elbow\" in the scree plot\n",
    "\n",
    "**Next:** [L11_clustering.ipynb](L11_clustering.ipynb) — K-means and EM algorithm."
   ]
  }
 ],
